{
  "text": "The overall reduction in taste in IBD patients can be well understood in the light of the manifold oral pathologies observed in these patients [CITATION_1] . These pathologies can be specific or non-specific manifestations. Moreover, the symptoms that are associated with these oral pathologies (specially acidic taste, taste changes, changes in the tongue and dry mouth) can be caused by iron, zinc, or vitamin deficiencies due to rectal bleeding and intestinal malabsorption linked to IBD, or its pharmacological treatments [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . It is also well known that zinc deficiency (regardless of its cause) is associated with taste dysfunction and losses in taste acuity [CITATION_5] .",
